         <ref id="ref2">
            <label>2.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">As<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>John Stuhr</string-name>
               </person-group>describes in his<source>
                  <italic>Genealogical Pragmatism: Philosophy, Experience, and Community</italic>
               </source>(<year>1997</year>), Dewey's transactional view of experience shows how what we experience and the ways we experience are “double barreled,” to use William James's phrase, for the transactional conveys “the irreducible unity of subject and object, organism and environment, foreground and background.” This interactive, co-constituting doubling feature of experience accounts for both “the primary, irreducible transactional character of experience, and the irreducible connections between meaning and existence”:<article-title>“Experience constitutes reality”</article-title>(<year>1997</year>,<fpage>128</fpage>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
